Closing Principle

The central hypothesis is not that binary computation is obsolete.

Rather,

there exist classes of problems whose natural representation is relational, dynamic, and field-based.

For those problems,

computing with gradients may be more natural than computing with isolated symbols.

The long-term vision is a computational architecture in which information is represented not only by discrete states but by the evolving geometry of relationships among them.

“Do not compute only with things.

Compute with relations among things.”

